			<div class="content" id="post-content-2462682">
									

<blockquote>
<p>(One old trick is supposed to be to say your dialogue out loud to see if it makes sense.)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Anyone reading should take this advice with a grain of salt, but I've found that speaking dialogue aloud doesn't give me the same feeling of realism because ultimately I am saying it in <em>my</em> voice - my vocal tone, my patterns of what words to emphasize in a sentence, etc. - and thus it's not the best for envisioning what a character totally different from me would say. Instead, I imagine that I'm watching the scene as if it's in a movie. I picture the characters and their physical appearances and what their voices sound like combined with events in the scenario that would affect how they speak (if they're afraid they'll stutter, so on and so forth) and from that I type out the sentence of dialogue and action.</p>
<p>(I say to take that with a grain of salt because personally/artistic medium-wise I resonate with movies and screenwriting the most. For all I know that amount of detail when envisioning a scene is overbearing.)</p>
